ip</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I03615X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research focuses upon how Politics and International Relations subfield International Political Economy (IPE) attends to its intellectual lineage and the implications that this holds for its articulation of individual agency. As such, this project aims to speak directly to two key debates in contemporary IPE:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>its recent historiographical turn&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>the associated debate over conceptualisations of individual economic agency therein. &lt;/li>

&lt;/ul>

&lt;p>To do this, Dr Glaze undertakes an in-depth comparison of the thought of Adam Smith and William James, respective ?fathers? of Economics and Psychology. Through this comparison&amp;nbsp; an alternative framework is developed through which individual agency can be conceptualised to that currently provided to IPE by neoclassical economics. Dr Glaze additionally traces Smith?s and James?s influence upon IPE in order to identify the implicit methodological barriers that impede its scholars? articulation of complex accounts of individual economic agency, as well as to evaluate their broader influence upon how the specialist subfield perceives its role, limits and future direction.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2012-11-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>74892</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>416DA833-CA41-4F3B-9FCB-19A37C3D7511</gtr:id><gtr:title>Adam Smith and William James on the psychological basis of progress</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Cambridge Journal of Economics</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/03e0bbaed84412d2c273dac453927197"><gtr:id>03e0bbaed84412d2c273dac453927197</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>S. Glaze</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2017-01-01</gtr:da